{"title_page": "Bita Moghaddam", "text_new": "{{short description|Iranian-American neuroscientist}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Bita Moghaddam\n| image             = File:Bita Moghaddam 2012.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = Iran\n| nationality       = Iranian-American\n| fields            = Neuroscience\n| workplaces        = Oregon Health Sciences University\n| alma_mater        = PhD at University of Kansas, Postdoctoral work at Yale University\n| known_for         = Discovery of first non-monoamine targeting compound for treatment of schizophrenia\n| awards            = Ruth Matarazzo Professor at OHSU, Paul Jansen Award for Excellence in Schizophrenia Research, Efron Award for Excellence in Research Related to Neuropsychopharmacology, 2014 CINP Neuroscience Basic Research Award, MERIT Award from the National Institute of Mental Health\n| Institutions      = Oregon Health and Science University\n}}\n'''Bita Moghaddam''' is an Iranian-American neuroscientist as well as a Professor of Behavioral Neuroscience and the Chair of the Department of Behavioral Neuroscience at [[Oregon Health & Science University|Oregon Health and Science University]]. Moghaddam investigates the neuronal processes underlying emotion and cognition as a first step to designing strategies to treat and prevent brain illnesses.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMoghaddam grew up in [[Iran]] with her mother, father, and sister.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> She was raised an environment where her parents emphasized the importance of education.<ref name=\":0\" />\u00a0 In the late 1970s, Moghaddam moved to the [[United States]] to pursue her education. She graduated ''summa cum lade'' from [[Avila University]] in 1982 with a major in chemistry and minor in mathematics. She moved on to the [[University of Kansas]] to work on her PhD.<ref name=\":0\" /> When Moghaddam started her graduate education, she had intentions to pursue her dissertation work in chemistry, but was inspired by one of her professors, Dr. Ralph Adams, and his innovative applications of [[analytical chemistry]] to understand brain chemistry.<ref name=\":0\" /> After becoming fascinated by the neural processes underlying [[schizophrenia]], Moghaddam decided to pursue a PhD, and a career, in neuroscience.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/bita-moghaddam/|title=Bita Moghaddam \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Under the mentorship of Dr. Ralph Adams, Moghaddam could learn from a pioneer in the field, how to build and apply electroanalytical tools to study schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://electroanalytical.org/Adams.html|title=Recollections - Ralph N. Adams|website=electroanalytical.org|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nDuring her PhD, Moghaddam worked on improving graphite electrodes for [[in vivo]] electrochemical experiments studying [[cationic]] primary neurotransmitters.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gerhardt|first=Greg A.|last2=Oke|first2=Arvin F.|last3=Nagy|first3=Geza|last4=Moghaddam|first4=Bita|last5=Adams|first5=Ralph N.|date=1984-01-09|title=Nafion-coated electrodes with high selectivity for CNS electrochemistry|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899384909636|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=290|issue=2|pages=390\u2013395|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(84)90963-6|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1986, Moghaddam published a first author paper in the [[Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences]] describing her improvements of the in vivo [[voltammetry]] method for applications in neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=B.|last2=Adams|first2=R. N.|date=1986|title=Recent Developments of in Vivo Voltammetry: Applications to Studies of Chemical Dynamics in the Neuronal Microenvironmenta|url=https://nyaspubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1749-6632.1986.tb27142.x|journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=481|issue=1|pages=106\u2013115|doi=10.1111/j.1749-6632.1986.tb27142.x|issn=1749-6632}}</ref> Moghaddam then published another first author paper highlighting her findings, using potassium-selective microelectrodes, that extracellular potassium concentrations vary across brain regions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Adams|first2=Ralph N.|date=1987-03-17|title=Regional differences in resting extracellular potassium levels of rat brain|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899387908031|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=406|issue=1|pages=337\u2013340|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(87)90803-1|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1987, Moghaddam completed her dissertation in which she simultaneously recorded the extracellular levels of both ions and neurotransmitters in the mammalian brain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elibrary.ru/item.asp?id=7530811|title=SIMULTANEOUS MONITORING OF EXTRACELLULAR ION AND NEUROTRANSMITTER LEVELS IN MAMMALIAN BRAIN.|website=www.elibrary.ru|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> After her PhD, Moghaddam pursued her postdoctoral training at [[Yale University]] in New Haven, Connecticut.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbrfoundation.org/about/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita Moghaddam, Ph.D.|date=2017-04-24|website=Brain & Behavior Research Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> At Yale, Moghaddam worked under the mentorship of Dr. Benjamin Bunney in the Department of Psychiatry exploring the modulatory effects of dopaminergic signalling in the striatum.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benhamin S.|date=1989|title=Differential effect of cocaine on extracellular dopamine levels in rat medial prefrontal cortex and nucleus accumbens: Comparison to amphetamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/syn.890040209|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=156\u2013161|doi=10.1002/syn.890040209|issn=1098-2396}}</ref>\u00a0Moghaddam published 6 first author papers during her three-year postdoctoral studies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=EX5b5sUAAAAJ&view_op=list_works&sortby=pubdate|title=Bita Moghaddam - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Moghaddem used the technique of in vivo [[microdialysis]] to look at the composition of extracellular [[dopamine]] in the rodent brain in various experimental preparations. She first discovered that the [[cocaine]] administration in rodents induced a higher magnitude increase in extracellular dopamine in the Nucleus Accumbens compared to the Medial Prefrontal Cortex.<ref name=\"auto5\"/> In the [[Journal of Neurochemistry]], she then reported the effects of perfusing solution on extracellular [[dopamine]] levels and the downstream effects this has on dopaminergic brain systems.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benjamin S.|date=1989|title=Ionic Composition of Microdialysis Perfusing Solution Alters the Pharmacological Responsiveness and Basal Outflow of Striatal Dopamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.1989.tb07383.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=53|issue=2|pages=652\u2013654|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.1989.tb07383.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref> Just before she began her faculty position at Yale, Moghaddam published another first author paper in the [[Journal of Neurochemistry]] reporting that administration of different antipsychotic drugs to rats has distinct effects on the release of dopamine in the Prefrontal Cortex, Nucleus Accumbens and the Striatum.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benjamin S.|date=1990|title=Acute Effects of Typical and Atypical Antipsychotic Drugs on the Release of Dopamine from Prefrontal Cortex, Nucleus Accumbens, and Striatum of the Rat: An In Vivo Microdialysis Study|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.1990.tb01230.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=54|issue=5|pages=1755\u20131760|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.1990.tb01230.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref>\n\n== Career and research ==\nIn 1990, Moghaddam started her first faculty position at [[Yale University]] in the Department of Psychiatry.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> She set up her lab to explore the neurobiology of midbrain dopamine neurons and prefrontal cortical subregions, key brain systems implicated in schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.moghaddamlab.org/about-the-lab/|title=About the Lab \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In a study published in Psychiatry in 1991, the Moghaddam lab reported that Ventral Tegmental Area dopamine neurons are activated both before stimulus onset, signifying an internal state of anticipation, in addition to firing in response to rewarding post-stimulus outcomes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Totah|first=Nelson K. B.|last2=Kim|first2=Yunbok|last3=Moghaddam|first3=Bita|date=2013-07-01|title=Distinct prestimulus and poststimulus activation of VTA neurons correlates with stimulus detection|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3727034/|journal=Journal of Neurophysiology|volume=110|issue=1|pages=75\u201385|doi=10.1152/jn.00784.2012|issn=0022-3077|pmc=3727034|pmid=23554430}}</ref> Moghaddam continued to collaborate with her postdoctoral mentor and others at Yale to explore the effects of typical schizophrenia medications on brain chemistry in vivo.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Daly|first=Darron A.|last2=Moghaddam|first2=Bita|date=1993-04-02|title=Actions of clozapine and haloperidol on the extracellular levels of excitatory amino acids in the prefrontal cortex and striatum of conscious rats|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304394093904832|journal=Neuroscience Letters|language=en|volume=152|issue=1|pages=61\u201364|doi=10.1016/0304-3940(93)90483-2|issn=0304-3940}}</ref>\n\nAs a young professor at Yale, Moghaddam started to hone in on the potential that aberrant glutamate signalling might be a large contributing factor to the pathology of schizophrenia, so she began to explore glutamate regulation and modulatory effects of glutamate in the brain regions associated with schizophrenia.<ref name=\":0\"/> In 1994, Moghaddam found that stress-induced dopamine release is controlled by local activation of [[ionotropic glutamate receptor]]s ([[AMPA receptor|AMPA]] receptors and [[Kainate receptor|kainate]] receptors).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jedema|first=H. P.|last2=Moghaddam|first2=B.|date=August 1994|title=Glutamatergic control of dopamine release during stress in the rat prefrontal cortex|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7518503|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|volume=63|issue=2|pages=785\u2013788|doi=10.1046/j.1471-4159.1994.63020785.x|issn=0022-3042|pmid=7518503}}</ref> A few years later, she found that [[Metabotropic glutamate receptor 5|metabotropic glutamate receptors]] regulate dopamine release in the striatum, adding to the understanding of the diverse interactions between glutamate and dopaminergic system in the brain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Verma|first=Anita|last2=Moghaddam|first2=Bita|date=1998|title=Regulation of striatal dopamine release by metabotropic glutamate receptors|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/%28SICI%291098-2396%28199803%2928%3A3%3C220%3A%3AAID-SYN5%3E3.0.CO%3B2-C|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=28|issue=3|pages=220\u2013226|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1098-2396(199803)28:33.0.CO;2-C|issn=1098-2396}}</ref> She also made a novel finding regarding the regulation of glutamate release during times of stress, such that glucocorticoids, released as a result of HPA axis activation, inhibit the stress-induced output of glutamate in the prefrontal cortex.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bolinao|first2=Maria L.|last3=Stein-Behrens|first3=Becky|last4=Sapolsky|first4=Robert|date=1994-08-29|title=Glucocortcoids mediate the stress-induced extracellular accumulation of glutamate|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899394916225|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=655|issue=1|pages=251\u2013254|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(94)91622-5|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1999, Moghaddam and her colleagues tested the compound LY354740, a metabotropic glutamate receptor agonist, which they found to suppress aberrant glutamate release, reduced behavioral disruptions in animals given PCP, and overall have less side effects than typical benzodiazepines used to treat certain symptoms of schizophrenia.<ref name=\":0\"/> These findings suggested that LY354740 could potentially be used to treat psychiatric and neurological disorders characterized by aberrant glutamate transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1999-11564-001|title=APA PsycNet|website=psycnet.apa.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Moghaddam was recruited to the University of Pittsburgh, and was the first faculty member in the Department of Neuroscience to be recruited straight to full professorship.<ref name=\":0\"/> At Pitt, Moghaddam took on more teaching roles than she had previously at Yale, and she became a critical mentor to many young undergraduate students hoping to pursue opportunities in neuroscience.<ref name=\":0\"/> At Pitt, Moghaddam made many contributions to the field of neuroscience by continuing to probe how modulation of glutamate signalling affects behavior and neural circuit function in models for anxiety and schizophrenia. She then expanded her laboratory focus to understanding [[glutamatergic]] interactions and dopaminergic systems in adolescence since many of the symptoms of psychiatric conditions emerge during adolescence and targeting aberrant functions during this developmental period will be essential to preventing onset of disease in adulthood.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Moghaddam joined the faculty at the Oregon Health Sciences University (OHSU) where she is the Chair of the Department of Behavioral Neuroscience as well as the Ruth Matarazzo Professor.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.osu.edu/events/bn-area-presents-bita-moghaddam-ph.d.|title=The BN Area Presents: Bita Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} Department of Psychology|website=psychology.osu.edu|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Moghaddam continues to probe the brain mechanisms involved in cognition and emotion in brain areas implicated in schizophrenia, anxiety, attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), and addiction, while also performing leaderships roles to oversee long-term planning and enhance collaboration within the OHSU behavioral neuroscience department.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In addition to her laboratory and departmental efforts, Moghaddam brings extensive teaching experience from her time at Pitt and participates in a large array of outreach efforts and initiatives to promote women in science and young students to pursue careers in science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nwnoggin.org/2018/05/26/diet-vs-brain/|title=Diet vs. Brain \u2013 NW NOGGIN: Neuroscience outreach group (growing in networks)|last=Griesar|first=Bill|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n\n* Ruth Matarazzo Professor at OHSU<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n* Paul Jansen Award for Excellence in Schizophrenia Research<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* Efron Award for Excellence in Research Related to Neuropsychopharmacology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://acnp.org/annual-meeting/honorific-grants/daniel-h-efron-research-previous-award-winners/|title=Daniel H. Efron Research Previous Award Winners|website=ACNP|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* 2014 CINP Neuroscience Basic Research Award<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* MERIT award from the National Institute of Mental Health<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n== Select publications ==\n\n* Del Arco, A., Park, J., Wood, J., Kim, Y., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Adaptive encoding of outcome prediction by prefrontal cortex ensembles supports behavioral flexibility. Journal of Neuroscience, 0450\u201317.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Bueno-Junior, L.S., Simon, N.W., Wegener, M.A., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Repeated Nicotine Strengthens Gamma Oscillations in the Prefrontal Cortex and Improves Visual Attention\u00a0 Neuropsychopharmacology 42 (8), 1590\u20131598.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Park, J., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Impact of anxiety on prefrontal cortex encoding of cognitive flexibility. Neuroscience 345, 193\u2013202.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Park, J., Wood, J., Bondi, C., Del Arco, A., and Moghaddam, B. (2016) Anxiety evokes hypofrontality and disrupts rule-relevant encoding by dorsomedial prefrontal cortex neurons. Journal of Neuroscience, 36(11): 3322\u20133335.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Lohani, S., Poplawsky, A.J., Kim, S.G., and Moghaddam, B. (2017) Unexpected global impact of VTA dopamine neuron activati on as measured by opto-fMRI. Molecular Psychiatry, doi:10.1038/mp.2016.102.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Kim, Y., Simon, N.W., Wood, J., and Moghaddam, B. (2015). Reward anticipation is encoded differently by adolescent VTA neurons. Biological Psychiatry, 79(11):878-86.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. and Gur, R.E. (2015). Women at the Podium: ACNP Strives to Reach Speaker Gender Equality at the Annual Meeting. Neuropsychopharmacology, 41(4):929-31.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Sturman, D.A., Moghaddam, B. (2012) The striatum processes reward differently in adolescents versus adults. Proceedings of the National Academy of Science, 109(5): 1719\u201324.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Darrah, J., Stefani, M.R., Moghaddam, B. (2008) Interaction of n-methyl-d-aspartate (NMDA) and group 5 metabotropic glutamate (mGlu5) receptors on behavioral flexibility using a novel operant set-shift paradigm. Behavioral Pharmacology, 19:225-234.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Moghaddam, B. (2004) Targeting metabotropic glutamate receptors for treatment of cognitive symptoms of schizophrenia. Psychopharmacology, 174:39-44.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Moghaddam, B. (2002) Stress activation of glutamate neurotransmission in the prefrontal cortex: Implications for dopamine-associated psychiatric disorders. Biological Psychiatry, 51:775-787.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Moghaddam, B. (1993) Stress preferentially activates extraneuronal levels of excitatory amino acids in the prefrontal cortex: A comparison to hippocampus and basal ganglia. Journal of Neurochemistry, 60:1650-1657.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Moghaddam, B., Roth, R.H., Bunney, B.S. (1990) Characterization of dopamine release in the rat prefrontal cortex as assessed by in vivo microdialysis: Comparison to the striatum. Neuroscience, 36:669-676.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Moghaddam, B., Adams, R.N. (1987) Regional differences in resting extracellular potassium levels of rat brain. Brain Research, 406:337-340.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Moghaddam, B., Schenk, J.O., Stewart, W.B., Hansen, A.J. (1987) Temporal relationship between neurotransmitter release and ion flux during spreading depression and anoxia. Canadian Journal of Physiology and Pharmacology, 65:1105-1110.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\n== Media coverage ==\n\n* Huffington Post, 22 March 2016, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/anxiety-bad-decisions_us_56eb2012e4b09bf44a9cd3ba \u201cAnxiety Could Be The Reason You Made A Bad Decision.\u201d] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/anxiety-bad-decisions_n_56eb2012e4b09bf44a9cd3ba|title=Anxiety Could Be The Reason You Made A Bad Decision|last=Gregoire|first=Carolyn|date=2016-03-22|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Psychology Today, 17 March 2016, \u201c[https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-athletes-way/201603/how-does-anxiety-short-circuit-the-decision-making-process How Does Anxiety Short Circuit the Decision-Making Process]?\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-athletes-way/201603/how-does-anxiety-short-circuit-the-decision-making-process|title=How Does Anxiety Short Circuit the Decision-Making Process?|website=Psychology Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Forbes, 29 October 2012, \u201c[http://www.forbes.com/sites/daviddisalvo/2012/10/29/new-study-shows-that-omega-3-supplements-can-boost-memory-in-young-adults/ New Study Shows that Omega-3 Supplements Can Boost Memory in Young Adults].\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/daviddisalvo/2012/10/29/new-study-shows-that-omega-3-supplements-can-boost-memory-in-young-adults/|title=New Study Shows that Omega-3 Supplements Can Boost Memory in Young Adults|last=DiSalvo|first=David|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* March 2016, \u201c[http://www.nature.com/multimedia/podcast/npp/npp_03212016.mp3 Women at the Podium: ACNP Strives to Reach Speaker Gender Equality at the Annual Meeting].\u201d \n* SfN's first-ever podcast on \"[http://neuronline.sfn.org/podcast The Perils of Publishing]\"\n\n== Personal life ==\nMoghaddam's father is from the city of [[Tuyserkan|Touyserkan]] and her mother from Tehran.<ref name=\":0\"/> Her father received a law degree from the [[University of Tehran]] in 1959 and served in the district attorney's office and then a judge for several decades. He is the author of several books in his native Persian including \u201cTouyserkan\u201d \u00a0\u062a\u0648\u064a\u0633\u0631\u0643\u0627\u0646 \u00a0on the history and culture of his birthplace. Moghaddam has been married to neuroscientist Charles W Bradberry since 1989. They have two children, Mazdak and Anahita.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moghaddam, Bita}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:American people of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:Avila University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Iranian-American neuroscientist}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Bita Moghaddam\n| image             = File:Bita Moghaddam 2012.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = Iran\n| nationality       = Iranian-American\n| fields            = Neuroscience\n| workplaces        = Oregon Health Sciences University\n| alma_mater        = PhD at University of Kansas, Postdoctoral work at Yale University\n| known_for         = Discovery of first non-monoamine targeting compound for treatment of schizophrenia\n| awards            = Ruth Matarazzo Professor at OHSU, Paul Jansen Award for Excellence in Schizophrenia Research, Efron Award for Excellence in Research Related to Neuropsychopharmacology, 2014 CINP Neuroscience Basic Research Award, MERIT Award from the National Institute of Mental Health\n| Institutions      = Oregon Health and Science University\n}}\n'''Bita Moghaddam''' is an Iranian-American neuroscientist as well as a Professor of Behavioral Neuroscience and the Chair of the Department of Behavioral Neuroscience at [[Oregon Health & Science University|Oregon Health and Science University]]. Moghaddam investigates the neuronal processes underlying emotion and cognition as a first step to designing strategies to treat and prevent brain illnesses.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMoghaddam grew up in [[Iran]] with her mother, father, and sister.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> She was raised an environment where her parents emphasized the importance of education.<ref name=\":0\" />\u00a0 In the late 1970s, Moghaddam moved to the [[United States]] to persue her education. She graduated ''summa cum lade'' from [[Avila University]] in 1982 with a major in chemistry and minor in mathematics. She moved on to the [[University of Kansas]] to work on her PhD.<ref name=\":0\" /> When Moghaddam started her graduate education, she had intentions to pursue her dissertation work in chemistry, but was inspired by one of her professors, Dr. Ralph Adams, and his innovative applications of [[analytical chemistry]] to understand brain chemistry.<ref name=\":0\" /> After becoming fascinated by the neural processes underlying [[schizophrenia]], Moghaddam decided to pursue a PhD, and a career, in neuroscience.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/bita-moghaddam/|title=Bita Moghaddam \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Under the mentorship of Dr. Ralph Adams, Moghaddam could learn from a pioneer in the field, how to build and apply electroanalytical tools to study schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://electroanalytical.org/Adams.html|title=Recollections - Ralph N. Adams|website=electroanalytical.org|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nDuring her PhD, Moghaddam worked on improving graphite electrodes for [[in vivo]] electrochemical experiments studying [[cationic]] primary neurotransmitters.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gerhardt|first=Greg A.|last2=Oke|first2=Arvin F.|last3=Nagy|first3=Geza|last4=Moghaddam|first4=Bita|last5=Adams|first5=Ralph N.|date=1984-01-09|title=Nafion-coated electrodes with high selectivity for CNS electrochemistry|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899384909636|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=290|issue=2|pages=390\u2013395|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(84)90963-6|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1986, Moghaddam published a first author paper in the [[Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences]] describing her improvements of the in vivo [[voltammetry]] method for applications in neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=B.|last2=Adams|first2=R. N.|date=1986|title=Recent Developments of in Vivo Voltammetry: Applications to Studies of Chemical Dynamics in the Neuronal Microenvironmenta|url=https://nyaspubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1749-6632.1986.tb27142.x|journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=481|issue=1|pages=106\u2013115|doi=10.1111/j.1749-6632.1986.tb27142.x|issn=1749-6632}}</ref> Moghaddam then published another first author paper highlighting her findings, using potassium-selective microelectrodes, that extracellular potassium concentrations vary across brain regions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Adams|first2=Ralph N.|date=1987-03-17|title=Regional differences in resting extracellular potassium levels of rat brain|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899387908031|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=406|issue=1|pages=337\u2013340|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(87)90803-1|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1987, Moghaddam completed her dissertation in which she simultaneously recorded the extracellular levels of both ions and neurotransmitters in the mammalian brain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elibrary.ru/item.asp?id=7530811|title=SIMULTANEOUS MONITORING OF EXTRACELLULAR ION AND NEUROTRANSMITTER LEVELS IN MAMMALIAN BRAIN.|website=www.elibrary.ru|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> After her PhD, Moghaddam pursued her postdoctoral training at [[Yale University]] in New Haven, Connecticut.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbrfoundation.org/about/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita Moghaddam, Ph.D.|date=2017-04-24|website=Brain & Behavior Research Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> At Yale, Moghaddam worked under the mentorship of Dr. Benjamin Bunney in the Department of Psychiatry exploring the modulatory effects of dopaminergic signalling in the striatum.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benhamin S.|date=1989|title=Differential effect of cocaine on extracellular dopamine levels in rat medial prefrontal cortex and nucleus accumbens: Comparison to amphetamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/syn.890040209|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=156\u2013161|doi=10.1002/syn.890040209|issn=1098-2396}}</ref>\u00a0Moghaddam published 6 first author papers during her three-year postdoctoral studies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=EX5b5sUAAAAJ&view_op=list_works&sortby=pubdate|title=Bita Moghaddam - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Moghaddem used the technique of in vivo [[microdialysis]] to look at the composition of extracellular [[dopamine]] in the rodent brain in various experimental preparations. She first discovered that the [[cocaine]] administration in rodents induced a higher magnitude increase in extracellular dopamine in the Nucleus Accumbens compared to the Medial Prefrontal Cortex.<ref name=\"auto5\"/> In the [[Journal of Neurochemistry]], she then reported the effects of perfusing solution on extracellular [[dopamine]] levels and the downstream effects this has on dopaminergic brain systems.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benjamin S.|date=1989|title=Ionic Composition of Microdialysis Perfusing Solution Alters the Pharmacological Responsiveness and Basal Outflow of Striatal Dopamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.1989.tb07383.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=53|issue=2|pages=652\u2013654|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.1989.tb07383.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref> Just before she began her faculty position at Yale, Moghaddam published another first author paper in the [[Journal of Neurochemistry]] reporting that administration of different antipsychotic drugs to rats has distinct effects on the release of dopamine in the Prefrontal Cortex, Nucleus Accumbens and the Striatum.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benjamin S.|date=1990|title=Acute Effects of Typical and Atypical Antipsychotic Drugs on the Release of Dopamine from Prefrontal Cortex, Nucleus Accumbens, and Striatum of the Rat: An In Vivo Microdialysis Study|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.1990.tb01230.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=54|issue=5|pages=1755\u20131760|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.1990.tb01230.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref>\n\n== Career and research ==\nIn 1990, Moghaddam started her first faculty position at [[Yale University]] in the Department of Psychiatry.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> She set up her lab to explore the neurobiology of midbrain dopamine neurons and prefrontal cortical subregions, key brain systems implicated in schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.moghaddamlab.org/about-the-lab/|title=About the Lab \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In a study published in Psychiatry in 1991, the Moghaddam lab reported that Ventral Tegmental Area dopamine neurons are activated both before stimulus onset, signifying an internal state of anticipation, in addition to firing in response to rewarding post-stimulus outcomes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Totah|first=Nelson K. B.|last2=Kim|first2=Yunbok|last3=Moghaddam|first3=Bita|date=2013-07-01|title=Distinct prestimulus and poststimulus activation of VTA neurons correlates with stimulus detection|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3727034/|journal=Journal of Neurophysiology|volume=110|issue=1|pages=75\u201385|doi=10.1152/jn.00784.2012|issn=0022-3077|pmc=3727034|pmid=23554430}}</ref> Moghaddam continued to collaborate with her postdoctoral mentor and others at Yale to explore the effects of typical schizophrenia medications on brain chemistry in vivo.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Daly|first=Darron A.|last2=Moghaddam|first2=Bita|date=1993-04-02|title=Actions of clozapine and haloperidol on the extracellular levels of excitatory amino acids in the prefrontal cortex and striatum of conscious rats|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304394093904832|journal=Neuroscience Letters|language=en|volume=152|issue=1|pages=61\u201364|doi=10.1016/0304-3940(93)90483-2|issn=0304-3940}}</ref>\n\nAs a young professor at Yale, Moghaddam started to hone in on the potential that aberrant glutamate signalling might be a large contributing factor to the pathology of schizophrenia, so she began to explore glutamate regulation and modulatory effects of glutamate in the brain regions associated with schizophrenia.<ref name=\":0\"/> In 1994, Moghaddam found that stress-induced dopamine release is controlled by local activation of [[ionotropic glutamate receptor]]s ([[AMPA receptor|AMPA]] receptors and [[Kainate receptor|kainate]] receptors).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jedema|first=H. P.|last2=Moghaddam|first2=B.|date=August 1994|title=Glutamatergic control of dopamine release during stress in the rat prefrontal cortex|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7518503|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|volume=63|issue=2|pages=785\u2013788|doi=10.1046/j.1471-4159.1994.63020785.x|issn=0022-3042|pmid=7518503}}</ref> A few years later, she found that [[Metabotropic glutamate receptor 5|metabotropic glutamate receptors]] regulate dopamine release in the striatum, adding to the understanding of the diverse interactions between glutamate and dopaminergic system in the brain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Verma|first=Anita|last2=Moghaddam|first2=Bita|date=1998|title=Regulation of striatal dopamine release by metabotropic glutamate receptors|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/%28SICI%291098-2396%28199803%2928%3A3%3C220%3A%3AAID-SYN5%3E3.0.CO%3B2-C|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=28|issue=3|pages=220\u2013226|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1098-2396(199803)28:33.0.CO;2-C|issn=1098-2396}}</ref> She also made a novel finding regarding the regulation of glutamate release during times of stress, such that glucocorticoids, released as a result of HPA axis activation, inhibit the stress-induced output of glutamate in the prefrontal cortex.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bolinao|first2=Maria L.|last3=Stein-Behrens|first3=Becky|last4=Sapolsky|first4=Robert|date=1994-08-29|title=Glucocortcoids mediate the stress-induced extracellular accumulation of glutamate|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899394916225|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=655|issue=1|pages=251\u2013254|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(94)91622-5|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1999, Moghaddam and her colleagues tested the compound LY354740, a metabotropic glutamate receptor agonist, which they found to suppress aberrant glutamate release, reduced behavioral disruptions in animals given PCP, and overall have less side effects than typical benzodiazepines used to treat certain symptoms of schizophrenia.<ref name=\":0\"/> These findings suggested that LY354740 could potentially be used to treat psychiatric and neurological disorders characterized by aberrant glutamate transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1999-11564-001|title=APA PsycNet|website=psycnet.apa.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Moghaddam was recruited to the University of Pittsburgh, and was the first faculty member in the Department of Neuroscience to be recruited straight to full professorship.<ref name=\":0\"/> At Pitt, Moghaddam took on more teaching roles than she had previously at Yale, and she became a critical mentor to many young undergraduate students hoping to pursue opportunities in neuroscience.<ref name=\":0\"/> At Pitt, Moghaddam made many contributions to the field of neuroscience by continuing to probe how modulation of glutamate signalling affects behavior and neural circuit function in models for anxiety and schizophrenia. She then expanded her laboratory focus to understanding [[glutamatergic]] interactions and dopaminergic systems in adolescence since many of the symptoms of psychiatric conditions emerge during adolescence and targeting aberrant functions during this developmental period will be essential to preventing onset of disease in adulthood.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Moghaddam joined the faculty at the Oregon Health Sciences University (OHSU) where she is the Chair of the Department of Behavioral Neuroscience as well as the Ruth Matarazzo Professor.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.osu.edu/events/bn-area-presents-bita-moghaddam-ph.d.|title=The BN Area Presents: Bita Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} Department of Psychology|website=psychology.osu.edu|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Moghaddam continues to probe the brain mechanisms involved in cognition and emotion in brain areas implicated in schizophrenia, anxiety, attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), and addiction, while also performing leaderships roles to oversee long-term planning and enhance collaboration within the OHSU behavioral neuroscience department.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In addition to her laboratory and departmental efforts, Moghaddam brings extensive teaching experience from her time at Pitt and participates in a large array of outreach efforts and initiatives to promote women in science and young students to pursue careers in science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nwnoggin.org/2018/05/26/diet-vs-brain/|title=Diet vs. Brain \u2013 NW NOGGIN: Neuroscience outreach group (growing in networks)|last=Griesar|first=Bill|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n\n* Ruth Matarazzo Professor at OHSU<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n* Paul Jansen Award for Excellence in Schizophrenia Research<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* Efron Award for Excellence in Research Related to Neuropsychopharmacology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://acnp.org/annual-meeting/honorific-grants/daniel-h-efron-research-previous-award-winners/|title=Daniel H. Efron Research Previous Award Winners|website=ACNP|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* 2014 CINP Neuroscience Basic Research Award<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* MERIT award from the National Institute of Mental Health<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n== Select publications ==\n\n* Del Arco, A., Park, J., Wood, J., Kim, Y., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Adaptive encoding of outcome prediction by prefrontal cortex ensembles supports behavioral flexibility. Journal of Neuroscience, 0450-17.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Bueno-Junior, L.S., Simon, N.W., Wegener, M.A., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Repeated Nicotine Strengthens Gamma Oscillations in the Prefrontal Cortex and Improves Visual Attention\u00a0 Neuropsychopharmacology 42 (8), 1590-1598.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Park, J., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Impact of anxiety on prefrontal cortex encoding of cognitive flexibility. Neuroscience 345, 193-202.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Park, J., Wood, J., Bondi, C., Del Arco, A., and Moghaddam, B. (2016) Anxiety evokes hypofrontality and disrupts rule-relevant encoding by dorsomedial prefrontal cortex neurons. Journal of Neuroscience, 36(11): 3322-3335.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Lohani, S., Poplawsky, A.J., Kim, S.G., and Moghaddam, B. (2017) Unexpected global impact of VTA dopamine neuron activati on as measured by opto-fMRI. Molecular Psychiatry, doi:10.1038/mp.2016.102.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Kim, Y., Simon, N.W., Wood, J., and Moghaddam, B. (2015). Reward anticipation is encoded differently by adolescent VTA neurons. Biological Psychiatry, 79(11):878-86.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. and Gur, R.E. (2015). Women at the Podium: ACNP Strives to Reach Speaker Gender Equality at the Annual Meeting. Neuropsychopharmacology, 41(4):929-31.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Sturman, D.A., Moghaddam, B. (2012) The striatum processes reward differently in adolescents versus adults. Proceedings of the National Academy of Science, 109(5): 1719-24.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Darrah, J., Stefani, M.R., Moghaddam, B. (2008) Interaction of n-methyl-d-aspartate (NMDA) and group 5 metabotropic glutamate (mGlu5) receptors on behavioral flexibility using a novel operant set-shift paradigm. Behavioral Pharmacology, 19:225-234.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Moghaddam, B. (2004) Targetting metabotropic glutamate receptors for treatment of cognitive symptoms of schizophrenia. Psychopharmacology, 174:39-44.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Moghaddam, B. (2002) Stress activation of glutamate neurotransmission in the prefrontal cortex: Implications for dopamine-associated psychiatric disorders. Biological Psychiatry, 51:775-787.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Moghaddam, B. (1993) Stress preferentially activates extraneuronal levels of excitatory amino acids in the prefrontal cortex: A comparison to hippocampus and basal ganglia. Journal of Neurochemistry, 60:1650-1657.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Moghaddam, B., Roth, R.H., Bunney, B.S. (1990) Characterization of dopamine release in the rat prefrontal cortex as assessed by in vivo microdialysis: Comparison to the striatum. Neuroscience, 36:669-676.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Moghaddam, B., Adams, R.N. (1987) Regional differences in resting extracellular potassium levels of rat brain. Brain Research, 406:337-340.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* Moghaddam, B., Schenk, J.O., Stewart, W.B., Hansen, A.J. (1987) Temporal relationship between neurotransmitter release and ion flux during spreading depression and anoxia. Canadian Journal of Physiology and Pharmacology, 65:1105-1110.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\n== Media coverage ==\n\n* Huffington Post, 22 March 2016, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/anxiety-bad-decisions_us_56eb2012e4b09bf44a9cd3ba \u201cAnxiety Could Be The Reason You Made A Bad Decision.\u201d] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/anxiety-bad-decisions_n_56eb2012e4b09bf44a9cd3ba|title=Anxiety Could Be The Reason You Made A Bad Decision|last=Gregoire|first=Carolyn|date=2016-03-22|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Psychology Today, 17 March 2016, \u201c[https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-athletes-way/201603/how-does-anxiety-short-circuit-the-decision-making-process How Does Anxiety Short Circuit the Decision-Making Process]?\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-athletes-way/201603/how-does-anxiety-short-circuit-the-decision-making-process|title=How Does Anxiety Short Circuit the Decision-Making Process?|website=Psychology Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Forbes, 29 October 2012, \u201c[http://www.forbes.com/sites/daviddisalvo/2012/10/29/new-study-shows-that-omega-3-supplements-can-boost-memory-in-young-adults/ New Study Shows that Omega-3 Supplements Can Boost Memory in Young Adults].\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/daviddisalvo/2012/10/29/new-study-shows-that-omega-3-supplements-can-boost-memory-in-young-adults/|title=New Study Shows that Omega-3 Supplements Can Boost Memory in Young Adults|last=DiSalvo|first=David|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* March 2016, \u201c[http://www.nature.com/multimedia/podcast/npp/npp_03212016.mp3 Women at the Podium: ACNP Strives to Reach Speaker Gender Equality at the Annual Meeting].\u201d \n* SfN's first-ever podcast on \"[http://neuronline.sfn.org/podcast The Perils of Publishing]\"\n\n== Personal life ==\nMoghaddam\u2019s father is from the city of [[Tuyserkan|Touyserkan]] and her mother from Tehran.<ref name=\":0\"/> Her father received a law degree from the [[University of Tehran]] in 1959 and served in the district attorney\u2019s office and then a judge for several decades. He is the author of several books in his native Persian including \u201cTouyserkan\u201d \u00a0\u062a\u0648\u064a\u0633\u0631\u0643\u0627\u0646 \u00a0on the history and culture of his birthplace. Moghaddam has been married to neuroscientist Charles W Bradberry since 1989. They have two children, Mazdak and Anahita. \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moghaddam, Bita}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:American people of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:Avila University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: persue \u2192 pursue, Targetting \u2192 Targeting, \u2019s \u2192 's (2), 0450-17 \u2192 0450\u201317 (5)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bita_Moghaddam"}
{"title_page": "Ivan Stewart (rugby league)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = Ivan Stewart\n|fullname       = Ivan Angus Stewart\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        =  \n|position       = {{rlp|HB}}\n|birth_date    = \n|birth_place = New Zealand\n|height         =  \n|weight         =  \n|club1          = [[City Rovers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1918\n|year1end       = 20\n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 3\n|teamA          = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearAstart     = 1919\n|yearAend       = \n|appearancesA   = 7\n|triesA         = 2\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    = 0\n|pointsA        = 6\n|teamB               = Auckland Province\n|yearBstart          =1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 1\n|triesB              = 0\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             = 0\n|teamC              = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearCstart          = 1920\n|yearCend            =  \n|appearancesC        = 1\n|triesC              = 0\n|goalsC              = 0\n|fieldgoalsC         = 0\n|pointsC             = 0\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\n'''Ivan Stewart''' played for the New Zealand rugby league team. He was Kiwi number 119 <ref name=\"New Zealand Rugby League player list\">{{cite web|url=https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/|title=NZRL player list|publisher=New Zealand Rugby League|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> and played one test, against Australia in 1919. He played for the [[City Rovers]] club in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition from 1918 to 1920.\n\n==Playing career==\nIvan Stewart debuted for the [[City Rovers]] in round one of the [[1918 Auckland Rugby League season|1918 season]]. He was part of the team who won the Roope Rooster that same season when they defeated Maritime 6\u20133 in the final at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 7,000 spectators.<ref>{{cite news \n| title = Northern Union/Roope Rooster Final/City Wins From Maritime\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume XLIX, Issue 209\n| date = 1918-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19180902.2.53\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref> He was named in the reserves to play in the Auckland match with Canterbury but did not take the field.\n\nStewart made his debut for [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] on the 1919 tour of [[Australia]]. In total he played in 6 of the 11 tour matches. He debuted in the 3rd tour match against Tamworth at halfback alongside the legendary [[Thomas McClymont]]. Stewart scored 2 tries in a 21\u201313 win.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Zealand v Tamworth\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/all-blacks-tour-1919/game-3/tamworth-vs-new-zealand.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref> These were to be his only points in a New Zealand jersey. He played centre against New South Wales Firsts in a 31\u201339 loss.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Zealand v New South Wales Firsts\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/all-blacks-tour-1919/game-5/nsw-firsts-vs-new-zealand.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref> And he played there again against the same opponents 2 days later when they again lost 19-22 <ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Zealand v New South Wales Firsts\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/all-blacks-tour-1919/game-6/nsw-firsts-vs-new-zealand.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref>\nStewart moved back to the halves for the match against Ipswich Firsts which New Zealand won 11\u20138.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Zealand v Ipswich Firsts\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/all-blacks-tour-1919/game-7/ipswich-vs-new-zealand.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref> Stewart played his fourth and fifth successive matches in 13\u201326,<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Zealand v Queensland Firsts\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/all-blacks-tour-1919/game-8/qld-firsts-vs-new-zealand.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref> and 13-16 point losses to Queensland<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Zealand v Queensland Firsts\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/all-blacks-tour-1919/game-9/qld-firsts-vs-new-zealand.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nAfter the tour of Australia (which involved no test matches) the [[Australia national rugby league team|Australian national team]] toured New Zealand. Stewart was selected to play for New Zealand against Australia at the Auckland Domain in the 4th test of the series.<ref>{{cite news \n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref> New Zealand trailed the series 1-2 and lost 32\u20132 in front of 15,000 spectators with Stewart playing halfback.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Zealand v Australia\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/new-zealand-vs-australia-1919/game-4/new-zealand-vs-australia/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref>  Stewart would get to play the Australian team again this time for the Auckland Province team made up of players from the Auckland club competition and the wider district although this particular team like most other Auckland Provincial teams in this era was totally dominated by [[Auckland Rugby League]] club players.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Province v Australia\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/kangaroos-tour-1919/game-5/auckland-province-vs-australia.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref> Auckland lost 8-32 which then went on to utterly demolish its remaining provincial opponents by well over 50 points.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Kangaroos Tour 1919 \n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 1920 Stewart played for the Auckland team which beat the touring England side 24\u201316 at the Auckland Domain in front of an enormous crowd estimated at 30,000.<ref>{{cite news \n| title = English Team Beaten/Opening Match of Tour/Auckland Scores 24 to 16/Good Display By Forwards\n| page = 6\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17532\n| date = 1920-07-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200726.2.79\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nIt is unclear if he continued to play in 1921 or beyond as there are no records of him playing rugby league or any other code in New Zealand.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Ivan}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:City Rovers players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = Ivan Stewart\n|fullname       = \n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        =  \n|position       = {{rlp|HB}}\n|birth_date    = \n|birth_place = New Zealand\n|height         =  \n|weight         =  \n|club1          = [[City Rovers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1918\n|year1e