y but did not take the field.\n\nStewart made his debut for [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] on the 1919 tour of [[Australia]]. In total he played in 6 of the 11 tour matches. He debuted in the 3rd tour match against Tamworth at halfback alongside the legendary [[Thomas McClymont]]. Stewart scored 2 tries in a 21\u201313 win.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Zealand v Tamworth\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/all-blacks-tour-1919/game-3/tamworth-vs-new-zealand.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref> These were to be his only points in a New Zealand jersey. He played centre against New South Wales Firsts in a 31\u201339 loss.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Zealand v New South Wales Firsts\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/all-blacks-tour-1919/game-5/nsw-firsts-vs-new-zealand.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref> And he played there again against the same opponents 2 days later when they again lost 19-22 <ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Zealand v New South Wales Firsts\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/all-blacks-tour-1919/game-6/nsw-firsts-vs-new-zealand.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref>\nStewart moved back to the halves for the match against Ipswich Firsts which New Zealand won 11\u20138.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Zealand v Ipswich Firsts\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/all-blacks-tour-1919/game-7/ipswich-vs-new-zealand.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref> Stewart played his fourth and fifth successive matches in 13\u201326,<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Zealand v Queensland Firsts\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/all-blacks-tour-1919/game-8/qld-firsts-vs-new-zealand.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref> and 13-16 point losses to Queensland<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Zealand v Queensland Firsts\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/all-blacks-tour-1919/game-9/qld-firsts-vs-new-zealand.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nAfter the tour of Australia (which involved no test matches) the [[Australia national rugby league team|Australian national team]] toured New Zealand. Stewart was selected to play for New Zealand against Australia at the Auckland Domain in the 4th test of the series.<ref>{{cite news \n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref> New Zealand trailed the series 1-2 and lost 32\u20132 in front of 15,000 spectators with Stewart playing halfback.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Zealand v Australia\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/new-zealand-vs-australia-1919/game-4/new-zealand-vs-australia/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref>  Stewart would get to play the Australian team again this time for the Auckland Province team made up of players from the Auckland club competition and the wider district although this particular team like most other Auckland Provincial teams in this era was totally dominated by [[Auckland Rugby League]] club players.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Province v Australia\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/kangaroos-tour-1919/game-5/auckland-province-vs-australia.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref> Auckland lost 8-32 which then went on to utterly demolish its remaining provincial opponents by well over 50 points.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Kangaroos Tour 1919 \n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url =https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 1920 Stewart played for the Auckland team which beat the touring England side 24\u201316 at the Auckland Domain in front of an enormous crowd estimated at 30,000.<ref>{{cite news \n| title = English Team Beaten/Opening Match of Tour/Auckland Scores 24 to 16/Good Display By Forwards\n| page = 6\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17532\n| date = 1920-07-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200726.2.79\n| accessdate = 2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nIt is unclear if he continued to play in 1921 or beyond as there are no records of him playing rugby league or any other code in New Zealand.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Ivan}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:City Rovers players]]\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivan_Stewart_(rugby_league)"}
{"title_page": "Eileen Harkin-Jones", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Eileen Harkin-Jones\n| birth_name = Eileen M. A. Harkin-Jones\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|FREng|FIMechE|FIChemE|size=100%}}\n| workplaces = [[Queen's University Belfast]] <br>[[Ulster University]]\n| alma_mater = [[University College Dublin]] (BEng)<br>[[Queen's University Belfast]] (PhD)\n| thesis_url = \thttp://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.317442\n| thesis_title = Rotational moulding of reactive plastics\n| thesis_year = 1992\n| fields = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Polymer]]s<ref name=gs/>\n* [[Polycaprolactone]]<ref name=gs/>\n* [[Nanocomposite]]s<ref name=gs/>\n* [[Composite material]]s<ref name=gs/>\n}}\n| website = {{URL|ulster.ac.uk/staff/e-harkin-jones}}\n}}\n\n'''Eileen M. A. Harkin-Jones''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|FREng|FIMechE|FIChemE}} is the [[Bombardier Aerospace]]-[[Royal Academy of Engineering]] professor of composites engineering at the [[Ulster University]].<ref name=gs>{{Google scholar id}}</ref><ref name=scopus>{{Scopus id}}</ref><ref name=\"MubarakHarkin-Jones2001\">{{cite journal|last1=Mubarak|first1=Y.|last2=Harkin-Jones|first2=E.M.A.|last3=Martin|first3=P.J.|last4=Ahmad|first4=M.|title=Modeling of non-isothermal crystallization kinetics of isotactic polypropylene|journal=Polymer|volume=42|issue=7|year=2001|pages=3171\u20133182|issn=0032-3861|doi=10.1016/S0032-3861(00)00606-6}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nHarkin-Jones studied mechanical engineering at [[University College Dublin]], and received first class honours in 1983.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iom3.org/materials-world-magazine/news/2015/feb/02/10-minutes-eileen-harkinjones|title=10 minutes with... Eileen Harkin-Jones|website=iom3.org|author=Anon|year=2015|language=en|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> She completed her [[PhD]] at [[Queen's University Belfast]]<ref name=ehjphd>{{cite thesis|degree=PhD|publisher=Queen's University of Belfast|url=https://copac.jisc.ac.uk/id/9551061?style=html|title=Rotational moulding of reactive plastics|first= Eileen M. A.|last=Harkin-Jones|date=1992|id={{EThOS|uk.bl.ethos.317442}}|website=jisc.ac.uk|oclc=53533917}}</ref> working on materials for rotational moulding in 1992.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://euronanoforum2015.eu/speaker/eileen-harkin-jones/|title=EuroNanoForum 2015|website=euronanoforum2015.eu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n\n== Research and career==\nHarkin-Jones was appointed a [[lecturer]] at Queen's in 1993.<ref name=\":1\"/> In 1999 Harkin-Jones became the first woman to be appointed an engineering professor in Ireland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://explore.cogentoa.com/cogent-engineering-section-editors|title=Cogent Engineering Editors {{!}} Explore Cogent OA|last=Francis|first=Thomas Jeatt for Taylor &|website=explore.cogentoa.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> Her research is on polymer processing and the development of materials.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qub.ac.uk/mrg/research/thermoforming/thermoforming.php|title=QUB MRG Group|website=qub.ac.uk|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> In 2015 she was appointed the [[Bombardier Aerospace|Bombardier]]-[[Royal Academy of Engineering]] professor of composite engineering at [[Ulster University]].<ref name=\":1\" /> At [[Ulster University]] she focuses on aerospace composites and sustainable plastic manufacture.<ref>{{Citation|publisher=Centre for Industrial Sustainability|title=Plastics: Design and Manufacture for Sustainability - Prof Eileen Harkin-Jones OBE|website=youtube.com|date=2015-07-16|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VtuDJ4pUJYg|accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newmaterials.com/News_Detail_Distinguished_engineer_appointed_to_drive_ulster_university_composites_research_capability_13437.asp|title=Distinguished engineer appointed to drive Ulster University composites research capability|website=newmaterials.com|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> Using [[injection moulding]], [[thermoforming]] and additive manufacture Harkin-Jones is exploring advanced [[thermoplastic]] composite materials for medical devices and aerospace.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.niace-centre.org.uk/index.php/our-team|title=Our Team|author=Anon|year=2018|website=niace-centre.org.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> She has published over 200 [[peer review]]ed papers,<ref name=gs/><ref name=scopus/> and secured funding over \u00a312 million.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nShe is a member of the [[Royal Academy of Engineering]] Higher Education committee and Deputy Chair of the Northern Ireland Higher Education Authority.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hefocus.raeng.org.uk/committee/professor-eileen-harkin-jones-obe-freng/|title=Professor Eileen Harkin-Jones OBE FREng |website=raeng.org.uk|publisher=Higher Education Hub|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hea.ie/assets/uploads/2017/04/368th-HEA-minutes-1.pdf|title=Higher Education Authority|author=Anon|date=2017|publisher=Higher Education Authority|website=hea.ie|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> She is campaigns for gender equality in [[science, technology, engineering, and mathematics]] (STEM) at a national level.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ria.ie/eileen-harkin-jones|title=Eileen Harkin-Jones|date=2016-02-18|publisher=[[Royal Irish Academy]]|website=ria.ie|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en}}</ref> She is a member of the All-Party Parliamentary Group for Manufacturing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.policyconnect.org.uk/apmg/people/prof-eileen-harkin-jones-obe|title=Prof Eileen Harkin Jones OBE {{!}} All-Party Parliamentary Manufacturing Group|website=policyconnect.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and honours===\nIn 2017 she was appointed a [[Fellow]] of the [[Irish Academy of Engineering]].<ref name=\":2\" /> She was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering]] (FREng) in 2011.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2013 she was appointed [[Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) for services to higher education.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/northern-ireland-citizens-receive-their-investitures|title=Northern Ireland citizens receive their Investitures|website=gov.uk|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ul.ie/news-centre/events/mssi-research-forum81/|title=MSSI Research Forum |publisher= University of Limerick|website=ul.ie|language=en|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harkin-Jones, Eileen}}\n[[Category:Irish women engineers]]\n[[Category:Irish mechanical engineers]]\n[[Category:Aerospace engineers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering]]\n[[Category:Female Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Queen's University Belfast]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish engineers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish engineers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:20th-century women engineers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women engineers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Eileen Harkin-Jones\n| birth_name = Eileen M. A. Harkin-Jones\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|FREng|FIMechE|FIChemE|size=100%}}\n| workplaces = [[Queen's University Belfast]] <br>[[Ulster University]]\n| alma_mater = [[University College Dublin]] (BEng)<br>[[Queen's University Belfast]] (PhD)\n| thesis_url = \thttp://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.317442\n| thesis_title = Rotational moulding of reactive plastics\n| thesis_year = 1992\n| fields = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Polymer]]s<ref name=gs/>\n* [[Polycaprolactone]]<ref name=gs/>\n* [[Nanocomposite]]s<ref name=gs/>\n* [[Composite material]]s<ref name=gs/>\n}}\n| website = {{URL|ulster.ac.uk/staff/e-harkin-jones}}\n}}\n\n'''Eileen M. A. Harkin-Jones''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|FREng|FIMechE|FIChemE}} is the [[Bombardier Aerospace]]-[[Royal Academy of Engineering]] professor of composites engineering at the [[Ulster University]].<ref name=gs>{{Google scholar id}}</ref><ref name=scopus>{{Scopus id}}</ref><ref name=\"MubarakHarkin-Jones2001\">{{cite journal|last1=Mubarak|first1=Y.|last2=Harkin-Jones|first2=E.M.A.|last3=Martin|first3=P.J.|last4=Ahmad|first4=M.|title=Modeling of non-isothermal crystallization kinetics of isotactic polypropylene|journal=Polymer|volume=42|issue=7|year=2001|pages=3171\u20133182|issn=0032-3861|doi=10.1016/S0032-3861(00)00606-6}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nHarkin-Jones studied mechanical engineering at [[University College Dublin]], and received first class honours in 1983.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iom3.org/materials-world-magazine/news/2015/feb/02/10-minutes-eileen-harkinjones|title=10 minutes with... Eileen Harkin-Jones|website=iom3.org|author=Anon|year=2015|language=en|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> She completed her [[PhD]] at [[Queen's University Belfast]]<ref name=ehjphd>{{cite thesis|degree=PhD|publisher=Queen's University of Belfast|url=https://copac.jisc.ac.uk/id/9551061?style=html|title=Rotational moulding of reactive plastics|first= Eileen M. A.|last=Harkin-Jones|date=1992|id={{EThOS|uk.bl.ethos.317442}}|website=jisc.ac.uk|oclc=53533917}}</ref> working on materials for rotational moulding in 1992.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://euronanoforum2015.eu/speaker/eileen-harkin-jones/|title=EuroNanoForum 2015|website=euronanoforum2015.eu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n\n== Research and career==\nHarkin-Jones was appointed a [[lecturer]] at Queen's in 1993.<ref name=\":1\"/> In 1999 Harkin-Jones became the first woman to be appointed an engineering professor in Ireland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://explore.cogentoa.com/cogent-engineering-section-editors|title=Cogent Engineering Editors {{!}} Explore Cogent OA|last=Francis|first=Thomas Jeatt for Taylor &|website=explore.cogentoa.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> Her research is on polymer processing and the development of materials.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qub.ac.uk/mrg/research/thermoforming/thermoforming.php|title=QUB MRG Group|website=qub.ac.uk|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> In 2015 she was appointed the [[Bombardier Aerospace|Bombardier]]-[[Royal Academy of Engineering]] professor of composite engineering at [[Ulster University]].<ref name=\":1\" /> At [[Ulster University]] she focuses on aerospace composites and suistanable plastic manufacture.<ref>{{Citation|publisher=Centre for Industrial Sustainability|title=Plastics: Design and Manufacture for Sustainability - Prof Eileen Harkin-Jones OBE|website=youtube.com|date=2015-07-16|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VtuDJ4pUJYg|accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newmaterials.com/News_Detail_Distinguished_engineer_appointed_to_drive_ulster_university_composites_research_capability_13437.asp|title=Distinguished engineer appointed to drive Ulster University composites research capability|website=newmaterials.com|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> Using [[injection moulding]], [[thermoforming]] and additive manufacture Harkin-Jones is exploring advanced [[thermoplastic]] composite materials for medical devices and aerospace.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.niace-centre.org.uk/index.php/our-team|title=Our Team|author=Anon|year=2018|website=niace-centre.org.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> She has published over 200 [[peer review]]ed papers,<ref name=gs/><ref name=scopus/> and secured funding over \u00a312 million.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nShe is a member of the [[Royal Academy of Engineering]] Higher Education committee and Deputy Chair of the Northern Ireland Higher Education Authority.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hefocus.raeng.org.uk/committee/professor-eileen-harkin-jones-obe-freng/|title=Professor Eileen Harkin-Jones OBE FREng |website=raeng.org.uk|publisher=Higher Education Hub|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hea.ie/assets/uploads/2017/04/368th-HEA-minutes-1.pdf|title=Higher Education Authority|author=Anon|date=2017|publisher=Higher Education Authority|website=hea.ie|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> She is campaigns for gender equality in [[science, technology, engineering, and mathematics]] (STEM) at a national level.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ria.ie/eileen-harkin-jones|title=Eileen Harkin-Jones|date=2016-02-18|publisher=[[Royal Irish Academy]]|website=ria.ie|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en}}</ref> She is a member of the All-Party Parliamentary Group for Manufacturing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.policyconnect.org.uk/apmg/people/prof-eileen-harkin-jones-obe|title=Prof Eileen Harkin Jones OBE {{!}} All-Party Parliamentary Manufacturing Group|website=policyconnect.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and honours===\nIn 2017 she was appointed a [[Fellow]] of the [[Irish Academy of Engineering]].<ref name=\":2\" /> She was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering]] (FREng) in 2011.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2013 she was appointed [[Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) for services to higher education.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/northern-ireland-citizens-receive-their-investitures|title=Northern Ireland citizens receive their Investitures|website=gov.uk|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ul.ie/news-centre/events/mssi-research-forum81/|title=MSSI Research Forum |publisher= University of Limerick|website=ul.ie|language=en|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harkin-Jones, Eileen}}\n[[Category:Irish women engineers]]\n[[Category:Irish mechanical engineers]]\n[[Category:Aerospace engineers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering]]\n[[Category:Female Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Queen's University Belfast]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish engineers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish engineers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:20th-century women engineers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women engineers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eileen_Harkin-Jones"}
